  "text": "I n atherogenesis, oxidatively modified lipids, particularly low-density lipoproteins (LDLs), accumulate in the arterial intima, [CITATION_1] where they are engulfed by myeloid cells. The resulting foam cells constitute a large component of early lesions. Foam cells are derived primarily from monocytes/ macrophages, 2,3 but the majority of research into the nature of foam cells has focused on relatively advanced lesions and has generally used a single monocyte/macrophage marker, such as CD68, MOMA-2, Mac-2, or Mac-3. 4 -6 Some of these markers (eg, CD68) can be expressed by both macrophages and dendritic cells (DCs) and thus cannot differentiate between these cell types. There are, however, several markers expressed preferentially by DCs, including CD11c, major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class II and 33D1 antigen. [CITATION_2] An in vitro study showed that macrophages, when treated with oxidatively modified lipids, differentiate into foam cells and in the process acquire expression of DC markers. [CITATION_3] The identity of foam cells is of great significance, because DCs possess distinct functions from macrophages and DC-derived foam cells may retain some or all of their properties.",
